        "content": "### FABS Positioning: Profiling the Distal Biceps Footprint\n\nThe distal biceps tendon runs **obliquely** to its radial-tuberosity footprint, so on standard planes it is foreshortened and partial-volumed — you cannot reliably grade a partial tear or measure retraction. **FABS** solves this.\n\n**FABS = Flexed elbow, ABducted shoulder, forearm Supinated**, with the patient **prone** and the arm overhead. This position lays the distal biceps tendon **flat and in-plane all the way to its radial-tuberosity footprint**, so you can:\n- Distinguish **partial** (some fibers still reaching the tuberosity) from **complete** (full discontinuity) tears\n- **Measure retraction** — where the stump sits, in cm\n- Assess the **bifurcated footprint** (short head distal/anterior, long head proximal/posterior)\n\n**Order FABS when the question is the distal biceps** — a middle-aged patient with a flexion-loading injury, antecubital ecchymosis, weak supination, or a positive hook test. The two management-changing variables FABS lets you report are **partial-vs-complete** and **retraction**, the features that drive repair urgency. (The lacertus-fibrosus status, the other key variable, is read on axial.)\n\n**Pitfall to avoid:** FABS is for the **distal biceps**, not the UCL — don't confuse the two when selecting positioning.",
        "pearl": "When the distal biceps is the question, add the FABS view (Flexed elbow, ABducted shoulder, Supinated forearm, prone) — it lays the tendon flat to its radial-tuberosity footprint so you can grade partial-vs-complete and measure retraction, which standard planes foreshorten."
