        "content": "### Grade and Locate: The Report That Drives the Decision\n\nThe surgeon needs three things from your read: **surface, location, and chronicity.** Give all three explicitly.\n\n**Surface / grade:**\n- **Sprain / low-grade** — periligamentous or intrasubstance edema, fibers grossly intact, no surface-reaching defect, no T-sign.\n- **Partial undersurface tear** — the T-sign; articular-sided, proximal fibers attached.\n- **Full-thickness** — **fluid-bright signal spanning the entire thickness with a gap/retraction, or medial extravasation through the defect.**\n\nA **<50% / >50% partial-thickness call is a useful descriptive heuristic, not a formally validated or named UCL grading scale.** Do not imply a validated cutoff drives the decision by itself.\n\n**Location:** name it — **proximal (humeral) / midsubstance / distal (sublime tubercle).** This is not cosmetic: **distal (sublime-tubercle) tears are clinically important, more often occult, and do worse nonoperatively**, which is exactly why naming the location matters. But distal-vs-proximal **predominance is genuinely not uniform in the literature** — teach the distal tear as a recognized, prognostically worse, under-recognized pattern, **not** as the more frequent lesion. **Proximal partials** are the ones favored for nonoperative/PRP management.\n\n**Chronicity:** a **thickened, heterogeneous, or ossified** ligament reads as **chronic**; clean acute fiber disruption reads as acute. The repair-vs-reconstruction conversation cares about **avulsion off bone (good tissue) vs a shredded chronic midsubstance.**\n\n| Axis | Acute / favorable | Chronic / unfavorable |\n|---|---|---|\n| Surface | Clean partial or avulsion | Diffuse attenuation |\n| Location | Proximal (better nonop/PRP) | Distal (worse nonop) |\n| Tissue | Avulsion off bone | Thickened/heterogeneous/ossified |",
