        "content": "### The Medial Triad and the Repair-vs-Reconstruction Conversation\n\nMedial-sided valgus overload **travels as a triad** — read all three on every thrower:\n\n| Component | What to document |\n|---|---|\n| **UCL anterior bundle** | Surface, location, chronicity (above) |\n| **Flexor-pronator (common flexor) origin** | Strain vs tendinosis off the medial epicondyle, overlying the UCL |\n| **Ulnar nerve** | Neuritis (caliber + T2 signal) and **flexion subluxation** in the cubital tunnel |\n\nA common incidental bony clue to chronic valgus overload is the **sublime-tubercle traction spur / ulnar traction marrow change**.\n\n**Management is driven by the lesion PLUS the athlete's demand, not the MRI alone:**\n- **Most partial/low-grade tears in throwers are managed nonoperatively first** — rest, flexor-pronator and kinetic-chain rehab, structured return-to-throwing; **PRP is increasingly used, especially for proximal partials.**\n- **Reconstruction (Tommy John, autograft)** is the conversation for **full-thickness tears in throwers wanting high-level return**, **high-grade/symptomatic partials that fail ~3–6 months of rehab**, or **valgus instability discordant with demand.**\n- **Repair ± internal brace** has re-emerged for **acute avulsion-type tears with good tissue**, particularly younger/lower-demand or earlier-return athletes — which is why the **avulsion-vs-shredded-midsubstance** distinction matters.\n\n**Two hedges to honor:** the failed-conservative interval, the repair-vs-reconstruction boundary, and PRP efficacy are all **evolving — present decision DRIVERS, not a rigid cutoff.** And **ulnar nerve transposition with reconstruction is selective**, done for preoperative ulnar symptoms or instability, not routinely.\n\n**The number MRI cannot give:** **dynamic valgus-stress ultrasound** quantifies side-to-side **medial ulnohumeral gapping** — a side-to-side difference of roughly **>1 mm (commonly cited ~1.5–2 mm)** is the functional instability threshold. For counseling, typical return is **~12–15 months after reconstruction vs ~6–9 months after repair + internal brace**, and prevention rests on **pitch-count/workload limits and avoiding breaking balls before skeletal maturity.**",
