        "content": "### PLRI and the Deep Tear Hiding Beneath Refractory 'Tennis Elbow'\n\n**Posterolateral rotatory instability (PLRI)** is **LUCL incompetence** that allows posterolateral subluxation of the radius and ulna off the capitellum — the lesion behind the clinical **lateral pivot-shift apprehension**. It is the **most common chronic/recurrent elbow instability** and follows:\n\n- **Dislocation or subluxation** (the LUCL is usually the primary lesion — see the O'Driscoll circle)\n- **Iatrogenic injury** from an **aggressive lateral epicondylitis release** or **radial-head surgery**\n\n**Why this is a satisfaction-of-search trap:** the **LUCL/RCL origin sits deep to the common extensor tendon**. A deep undersurface tear at that origin can hide beneath what reads as routine lateral epicondylitis. This is **the lesion that converts refractory 'tennis elbow' into instability** — and it is a classic complication of prior **lateral corticosteroid injection or surgical release**.\n\n**What separates the surgical lesion from over-call:**\n\n| Finding | Interpretation |\n|---|---|\n| Thickened, T2-bright common extensor, **intact deep fibers** | Tendinosis / partial CET tear → conservative |\n| **Fluid-bright gap** at the origin that **undercuts/communicates with the radiocapitellar joint AND involves the LUCL** | Deep tear implying **PLRI → surgical** |\n| Reactive lateral-epicondyle marrow edema, **thin RCL signal alone** | **Normal/reactive — do NOT call an LCL tear** |\n\n**Always trace the LUCL to the supinator crest before signing off any high-grade lateral epicondylitis.** The companion ligament is where the surgery hides.",
        "pearl": "A deep common-extensor tear with a fluid-bright gap that undercuts the radiocapitellar joint and involves the LUCL is PLRI, not tennis elbow — it is a known complication of prior lateral injection/release and turns a debridement into a ligament reconstruction."
