        "content": "### Anteromedial Coronoid Facet Fracture and VPMRI\n\n**Varus posteromedial rotatory instability (VPMRI)** is the **third, distinct instability mechanism** — separate from valgus instability and from PLRI. Its imaging signature is an **anteromedial coronoid facet fracture + LUCL injury**.\n\nThe critical teaching point: the **anteromedial facet fragment looks small on radiographs but is highly unstable and surgical.** Untreated VPMRI drives **early arthrosis**. This is a classic **don't-miss** MRI/CT call — **small does not mean stable at the coronoid.**\n\n**Two coronoid classifications — use them for different things:**\n\n| System | Classifies | Scheme |\n|---|---|---|\n| **O'Driscoll** | The **anteromedial facet** (the VPMRI lesion) | Anteromedial-facet subtypes |\n| **Regan-Morrey** | Coronoid **height** | I = tip avulsion · II = ≤50% · III = >50% of coronoid height |\n\nThe coronoid is the **keystone of terrible-triad reconstruction**, which is why height matters surgically (Regan-Morrey), while the **anteromedial facet** specifically flags the **varus posteromedial mechanism** (O'Driscoll).\n\n**Practical read:** in any post-trauma elbow, sweep the coronoid for **both** a height loss and an anteromedial-facet fragment. **CT maps the osseous fragment best** and is often added for surgical planning.",
        "pearl": "An anteromedial coronoid facet fracture is small on radiographs but means varus posteromedial rotatory instability — a distinct, surgical instability that drives early arthrosis if missed; classify the facet with O'Driscoll and coronoid height with Regan-Morrey."
