        "content": "### Terrible Triad, Osborne-Cotterill, HO, and the Management Hinge\n\n**The terrible triad** = **elbow dislocation + radial head fracture + coronoid fracture.** It is recognizable on MRI/CT and is **surgical**, with the **coronoid and LCL as the reconstructive keystones**.\n\nAfter any dislocation, run the post-traumatic circle and look for two more findings:\n\n- **Osborne-Cotterill lesion** — a **posterolateral capitellar impaction fracture + posterolateral capsular avulsion**. It is the **lateral analog of a Hill-Sachs**, perpetuates **recurrent PLRI**, and is a clue to **occult instability**.\n- **Post-traumatic heterotopic ossification (HO)** — a common, **function-limiting cause of the stiff elbow** that changes management (timing of excision, indomethacin/radiation prophylaxis).\n\n**The management hinge:**\n\n| Scenario | Disposition |\n|---|---|\n| Acute LUCL injury after dislocation, elbow **concentrically reduced and stable** | Often **nonoperative** |\n| **Persistent/recurrent PLRI** | **LUCL repair or reconstruction** |\n| **Iatrogenic LUCL injury** (lateral release / radial-head surgery) | Recognized cause of **acquired PLRI** → surgical |\n| **Anteromedial coronoid facet fracture (VPMRI)** | **Surgical** |\n| **Terrible triad** | **Surgical** — coronoid + LCL keystones |\n\nSo the disposition turns on **whether the joint stays concentrically reduced**: a stable, reduced elbow with an LUCL injury can be treated nonoperatively, whereas recurrent PLRI, VPMRI, and the terrible triad all go to surgery.",
