        "content": "### Lateral Epicondylitis (ECRB) and Tracing the LUCL\n\n'Tennis elbow' is **angiofibroblastic TENDINOSIS, not inflammation**, of the **common extensor origin** — the **ECRB is the principal culprit** — off the **lateral epicondyle**. Grade it on the same ladder you use elsewhere:\n\n| Grade | Appearance |\n|---|---|\n| **Tendinosis** | Thickening + **intermediate signal**, no surface-reaching fluid/gap |\n| **Partial** | **Fluid-bright** signal reaching a surface or a focal discontinuity, **intact deep fibers** |\n| **Full-thickness** | Complete **fluid-bright gap** at the origin |\n\n**The management-changing step: ALWAYS trace the LUCL to the supinator crest.** The LUCL/RCL origin lies **deep to the common extensor tendon**, so a deep tear can extend into the ligament. A **deep/full-thickness common-extensor tear with a fluid-bright gap that undercuts or communicates with the radiocapitellar joint and involves the LUCL implies PLRI (posterolateral rotatory instability)** — this converts a routine extensor debridement into a **ligament repair/reconstruction**, and it is a **known complication of prior lateral steroid injection or surgical release**.\n\n**Two cautions:**\n- **Do not over-call** associated **reactive lateral-epicondyle marrow edema** or a **thin reactive RCL signal** as an LCL tear.\n- **Corticosteroid injection gives only short-term benefit and may worsen long-term outcomes** — frame expectations accordingly.",
        "pearl": "Never sign off a high-grade lateral epicondylitis without tracing the LUCL to the supinator crest: a deep extensor tear that undercuts the radiocapitellar joint and involves the LUCL means PLRI and turns a debridement into a ligament reconstruction."
