        "content": "### Medial Epicondylitis and the Medial Valgus Triad\n\n'Golfer's elbow' is **common flexor-pronator tendinosis** off the medial epicondyle — **less common than lateral epicondylitis** but graded on the **same tendinosis → partial → full-thickness ladder**. The common flexor-pronator tendon **overlies the UCL**, which is exactly why the medial read cannot stop at the tendon.\n\n**Read the medial side as a triad** (the three structures that travel together and fail together, especially in throwers):\n\n| Component | Trace to | Why it matters |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Common flexor-pronator** | Medial epicondyle origin | The epicondylitis itself |\n| **UCL (anterior bundle)** | **Sublime tubercle** of the coronoid | A concomitant tear shifts a thrower toward **reconstruction** |\n| **Ulnar nerve** | **Cubital tunnel**, immediately posterior | Co-existing neuritis changes symptoms and treatment |\n\n**The key linkage:** medial epicondylitis and UCL injury **frequently coexist**, and a **concomitant UCL tear changes the conversation toward reconstruction in a thrower** — so trace the **anterior bundle of the UCL to the sublime tubercle** and interrogate the **ulnar nerve** on every medial-pain study.\n\n**Strain framework (applies to both sides):** the universal grade **1/2/3** scheme covers flexor-pronator and extensor **muscle** strains — **grade 1** = feathery perifascial edema with intact architecture; **grade 2** = fiber disruption with focal fluid/hematoma; **grade 3** = complete discontinuity with retraction, most common at the **myotendinous junction**.",
