        "content": "### Ulnar Nerve / Cubital Tunnel: the Internal-Control Technique\n\nThe **cubital tunnel** is the most common site of elbow neuropathy and the **second most common compression neuropathy overall** (after carpal tunnel). The ulnar nerve runs **between the medial epicondyle and the olecranon, beneath the cubital tunnel retinaculum (Osborne's)**, where it is superficial, angulated, and stretched in flexion.\n\n**What to report (best on axial):**\n- **Caliber enlargement and T2 hyperintensity at or just distal to the medial epicondyle.**\n- **Denervation of the ulnar-innervated muscles: FCU, ulnar (medial) half of FDP, and the ulnar intrinsics** of the hand — the localizing secondary sign.\n- A structural cause: **anconeus epitrochlearis**, ganglion, osteophyte, or the medial valgus-overload changes.\n\n**The technique that fixes the absent CSA cutoff:** there is **no validated universal cross-sectional-area threshold**, and **mild T2 brightness can be normal**. Assess at the **medial-epicondyle level** and compare the nerve's caliber and signal to **two internal controls**:\n\n| Comparator | Why |\n|---|---|\n| **Contralateral ulnar nerve** | Side-to-side asymmetry flags abnormal enlargement/signal |\n| **Ipsilateral MEDIAN nerve** | A same-arm normal nerve calibrates 'how bright is too bright' |\n\nAnchor the diagnosis to **caliber change + denervation + clinical correlation**, not signal alone. The ulnar nerve is the **third member of the medial valgus-overload triad** in throwers — with the UCL and the flexor-pronator origin — so on a thrower's medial-pain study, read all three.\n\n**Management:** a structural, denervating cubital-tunnel lesion goes to decompression; isolated mild signal without caliber change or denervation does not.",
