        "content": "### Median / AIN: Pure-Motor Palsy, the Parsonage-Turner Caveat & Pronator Syndrome\n\nTwo distinct median-nerve syndromes at the elbow — keep them separate, because one of them often shouldn't go to surgery.\n\n**Anterior interosseous nerve (AIN, Kiloh–Nevin) — PURE MOTOR.** It denervates **flexor pollicis longus (FPL), FDP to the index/middle fingers, and pronator quadratus**, producing **weak pinch (an abnormal 'OK' sign) and NO sensory loss**. On MRI, look for the localizing pattern — **classically isolated pronator quadratus edema** (subacute) on axial fat-sat images.\n\n**The caveat that stops a surgeon:** an AIN palsy is **frequently neuralgic amyotrophy (Parsonage–Turner)**, NOT a mechanical compression. So **surgery is usually NOT indicated**; the work-up pivots to **EMG and observation**, and the history search turns to a **viral/post-vaccination prodrome or a broader brachial-plexus pattern** (other muscles outside a single nerve territory). Don't reflexively route isolated PQ/FPL denervation to decompression.\n\n**Pronator syndrome — MIXED sensory + motor.** This is **median-nerve compression** more proximally, at one of several sites:\n\n| Compression site |\n|---|\n| Between the two heads of **pronator teres** |\n| Under the **lacertus fibrosus** |\n| At the **FDS (sublimis) arch** |\n| **Ligament of Struthers** (watch for a bony **supracondylar process**) |\n\nUnlike isolated AIN palsy, pronator syndrome has **sensory symptoms** (volar forearm/hand) plus motor findings; on MRI hunt the supracondylar process and any mass at these sites.\n\n**Management:** isolated pure-motor AIN palsy → think Parsonage–Turner, EMG/observation; a demonstrable structural compressive cause → decompression.",
