        "content": "### Infection: Septic Bursa vs Septic Joint vs Osteomyelitis\n\nThe elbow is a common site for **olecranon bursitis**, and the single most important teaching point is a limitation, not a sign: **MRI cannot reliably exclude infection.**\n\n- A **red, warm, fluctuant olecranon bursa** needs **ASPIRATION**, not just imaging. Do not let a normal-looking or 'reactive' MRI talk a clinician out of tapping a bursa that is clinically inflamed.\n- **Aseptic bursitis** is caused by **gout, rheumatoid arthritis, and repetitive trauma** — the picture can overlap completely with septic bursitis on MRI.\n\nWhen the deeper compartments are involved, the threshold to escalate drops fast:\n\n| Process | Imaging clue | Don't-miss point |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Septic bursitis** | Distended bursa ± rim enhancement | MRI cannot exclude it — **aspirate the warm bursa** |\n| **Septic joint** | **Joint effusion + aggressive periarticular edema + rim enhancement** | Escalate urgently; not a rehab problem |\n| **Osteomyelitis** | Marrow edema/replacement with cortical involvement | Cannot be confidently separated from aggressive inflammation on signal alone |\n\n**Joint effusion plus aggressive periarticular edema and rim-enhancement escalates urgently.** The role of MRI here is to **map extent and raise the alarm**, not to grant clearance — the diagnosis is made by **aspiration and the clinical picture**.",
